			<div class="title">
				Creating "Envoyer" #NapknAppWeek3
			</div>
		  <div class="media-body">
		    <h4 class="media-heading"><i>Post By: <a href="http://twitter.com/zachwhelchel">Zach Whelchel</a> & <a href="http://twitter.com/rtseidel">Taylor Seidel</a>, September 4th, 2015</i></h4>
		  </div>
			<br>
			<br>
			<br>
			<div class="answer">
				<p><a href="/apps/envoyer">Envoyer</a> came from my (Taylor's) desire to recreate the excitement of writing and receiving letters. Today’s messages are always instant… let's bring back the anticipation.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="question" style="margin-top: 60px">
				Idea (Taylor)
			</div>
			<div class="answer">
				<p>I wanted to create an app that restores some of the excitement and romance to the standard messaging app. By definition, all of the messaging apps out there share everything instantly and save your whole conversation forever unless you delete it. Most apps will even share exactly when you are typing! When you can see everything at once, there are no surprises!</p>
				<p>We are fortunate to have the technology that we no longer have to rely on letters and the post office to communicate over long distances, but we've lost a lot in the process. The delight in crafting a really excellent letter; the touch of sealing it and posting it; sending it out into the world; the anticipation of waiting for a letter to arrive; and the excitement and pleasure of finally opening a friend's letter. Letter writing, from friends passing notes in class to lovers writing across great distances, is a dying art form.</p>
				<p>With Envoyer, you are able to send not only messages but the whole “collection of letters” back and forth. Like dropping the letter back in the mail, the chain disappears from the user's phone until the receiver responds.</p>
				<p>Enjoyer won’t replace email, group messaging, or text, but we thought there was an audience who would enjoy communicating with their friends and significant others in a less business-like, more whimsical way. So we created Envoyer.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="question" style="margin-top: 60px">
				Skeuomorphism (Zach)
			</div>
			<div class="answer">
				<p>Skeuomorphism as a standard design style is dead. But is there still a place for it? Rarely? Especially in contexts that are meant to replicate “old school” actions?</p>
				<br>
				<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-align-center" lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">Skeuomorphism is out, agreed. But is there a time/place for it? Especially when capturing old activity like letter writing? <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/NapknAppWeek3?src=hash">#NapknAppWeek3</a></p>&mdash; Zach Whelchel (@ZachWhelchel) <a href="https://twitter.com/ZachWhelchel/status/623214341458948096">July 20, 2015</a></blockquote> <script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
				<br>
				<p>I wanted to explore both routes initially and get some feedback from the community. I posted two directions for design and the people decided.</p>
				<br>
