				<br>
				<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-align-center" data-conversation="none" lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/ZachWhelchel">@ZachWhelchel</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/NapknApps">@NapknApps</a> clean looks better to me</p>&mdash; Rafael F. Silva (@rfsbsb) <a href="https://twitter.com/rfsbsb/status/623218073005387776">July 20, 2015</a></blockquote> <script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
				<br>
				<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-align-center" data-conversation="none" lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/ZachWhelchel">@ZachWhelchel</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/NapknApps">@NapknApps</a> Clean all the way</p>&mdash; Troy Rizzo (@troyrizzo) <a href="https://twitter.com/troyrizzo/status/623372419374317568">July 21, 2015</a></blockquote> <script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
				<br>
				<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-align-center" data-conversation="none" lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr"><a href="https://twitter.com/troyrizzo">@troyrizzo</a> <a href="https://twitter.com/ZachWhelchel">@ZachWhelchel</a> the people have spoken. Clean it is. New mockups coming soon.</p>&mdash; Napkn Apps (@NapknApps) <a href="https://twitter.com/NapknApps/status/623510855783723009">July 21, 2015</a></blockquote> <script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
			</div>
			<div class="question" style="margin-top: 60px">
				Decisions (Taylor)
			</div>
			<div class="answer">
				<p>The decisions we made revolved around how feature rich we wanted our messaging process to be. Interestingly enough we found that the more we stripped the more the app felt "like mail." We decided to nix push notifications, for example, so that you had to “go check the mail.” We also initially toyed around with the idea of letters being sent at variable speeds based on the user’s distance to the recipient.</p> 
				<br>
				<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-align-center" lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">Decisions that need to be made for <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/NapknAppWeek3?src=hash">#NapknAppWeek3</a>. Leaning towards the whole right column. Thoughts <a href="https://twitter.com/rtseidel">@rtseidel</a>? <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/MVP?src=hash">#MVP</a> <a href="http://t.co/2dCnuAEkE4">pic.twitter.com/2dCnuAEkE4</a></p>&mdash; Zach Whelchel (@ZachWhelchel) <a href="https://twitter.com/ZachWhelchel/status/624265229912932353">July 23, 2015</a></blockquote> <script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
			</div>
			<div class="question" style="margin-top: 60px">
				Development (Zach)
			</div>
			<div class="answer">
				<p>We spent a lot of time on unique UI interactions. We created a custom “letter stack” cell that visually showed the letters you had sent back and forth with a friend. The goal was to make the simple process visually rewarding. The more letters you sent the fuller the experience felt. Letter’s also fanned open so that you could review past “threads."</p>
				<br>
				<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-align-center" lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">Letter stack open and close animations, thoughts? <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/NapknAppWeek3?src=hash">#NapknAppWeek3</a> <a href="http://t.co/jQ4wK32ba8">pic.twitter.com/jQ4wK32ba8</a></p>&mdash; Zach Whelchel (@ZachWhelchel) <a href="https://twitter.com/ZachWhelchel/status/623578117102305280">July 21, 2015</a></blockquote> <script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
				<br>
				<p>The main difficulty we ran into was a fitting user account structure. We wanted to give each user an “address” at which they could be reached. We wanted this to be public, as if you knew anyone’s P.O. Box number. We thought the perfect modern equivalent would be someone’s Twitter handle. To verify handle’s we had user’s log in with Twitter. We would then save their handle and use it to send them messages. But then...</p>
				<br>
				<blockquote class="twitter-tweet tw-align-center" lang="en"><p lang="en" dir="ltr">Update on <a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/NapknAppWeek3?src=hash">#NapknAppWeek3</a>, App Store won&#39;t accept an app that requires Twitter login w/o Twitter specific features. Resubmitting...</p>&mdash; Napkn Apps (@NapknApps) <a href="https://twitter.com/NapknApps/status/632226302498603008">August 14, 2015</a></blockquote> <script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
				<br>
				<p>Envoyer was rejected from the App Store for using Twitter authentication without using “Twitter specific features.” This was a pretty big bummer as the only solution was to switch to a custom username. You now need to ask a friend for their username before you can correspond with them. We thought it a bit much that Apple would regulate this, since Twitter’s terms have nothing against such a use… but conceded that as a whole the App Store is likely better off for such restrictions. Apple is mainly safeguarding from requiring users to have third party accounts for apps that don’t strictly need them. Ours was just an interesting in-between case.</p>
				<p>The finished UI was simple and clean. We trimmed my skeuomorphic desires down to only the inclusion of a script font. The rest feels rather clean and straightforward.</p>
